<br>
I didn't do anything different in PVP from normal except I made sure my bear had sow.  When I picked a target, the bear stayed on them and stunned them quite a bit.  I added in as much damage as possible to keep them interrupted.  They'd run some more to try and get distance (thinking the pet had no sow) and die.  <br>
<br>
Jousting better helped a lot.  The bear's continuous hounding at their heels was great.  Having to shift tactics for the wide array of folks so rapidly was a lot of fun.<br>
<br>
Group PVP, we're not so bad.  If a snare lands, and you don't pumice off the dots, you're dead.  You have to pumice dots, you don'[t heal that well.<br>
<br>
By the end of the night folks were ganging up on me, a good sign that the beastlord class had opened their eyes.<br>
<br>
I'm only level 35, but even the level 60 warriors went nuts with the bear on their tails while they chased me round and round the arena.  A time or two, the bear died and I channeled through lots of hits to get another one up, then channeled some more to give him his level buff and run some more.  <br>
<br>
The bst slows stuck pretty well but not the dots.  <br>
<br>
The big advantage was the pure chaos of mass pvp and that when people look at a beastlord, they see bad armor (the impression isn't particularly fearsome).  <br>
<br>
